  "prompt": "What's the difference between voltage, current, and watts?",
  "response": "Voltage, current, and watts are fundamental concepts in electricity and are closely related but distinct.\n\n1. **Voltage (V)**:\n   - **Definition**: Voltage, also known as electric potential difference, is the force that pushes electric charge through a circuit. It is measured in volts (V).\n   - **Analogy**: Think of voltage as the pressure in a water pipe. Just as water pressure pushes water through a pipe, voltage pushes electric charge through a wire.\n   - **Formula**: Voltage (V) = Current (I) \u00d7 Resistance (R), as per Ohm's Law (V = IR).\n\n2. **Current (I)**:\n   - **Definition**: Current is the flow of electric charge through a conductor. It is measured in amperes (A), often simply called amps.\n   - **Analogy**: Current is like the amount of water flowing through the pipe. The higher the current, the more charge is flowing per unit of time.\n   - **Formula**: Current (I) = Voltage (V) \u00f7 Resistance (R), also derived from Ohm's Law (I = V/R).\n\n3. **Watts (W)**:\n   - **Definition**: Watts represent power, which is the rate of energy transfer or the rate at which work is done. It is measured in watts (W).\n   - **Analogy**: Power (watts) is like the rate at which water is delivered, considering both the pressure (voltage) and the flow rate (current).\n   - **Formula**: Power (P) = Voltage (V) \u00d7 Current (I), given by P = VI.\n\nIn summary:\n- **Voltage** is the electric potential difference that drives the current.\n- **Current** is the flow of electric charge.\n- **Watts** are a measure of the power, which combines both voltage and current to describe the rate of energy use or transfer.\n\nThese concepts are interconnected, and understanding their relationships is crucial for working with electrical systems.",
